(63, 'Server operation is not a commodity', 'server-operation-is-not-a-commodity', 1, 1, '<p>Many developers consider hosting and server as commodities. It''s something they buy from a datacenter company or different forms of virtualization or platforms as services. Business owners are similar to electricity or other utilities - servers work, do not need to do it, and get an account for them. It is true that server infrastructure, whether in real or virtual form, is becoming more and more simple to operate. Clients, however, often encounter unoccupied space that is not completely under control. The operator can deliver a great added value in this direction, which saves a lot of costs, but especially stress on all sides. Is the fact that the operator has launched several dozen applications that were most likely to have even higher performance and availability requirements? Is it worthwhile to cooperate with a company that can keep applications running for years and not "get in touch" with technological developments, just the opposite, and improve on the operating site?</p>\r\n<p>Scalability, redundancy, and performance are often marginalized in the development of applications or are only addressed at the last minute. When fine-tuning the application that is not ready for sharp operation, it is rarely necessary to spend up to a dozen additional human readings. The developer''s priority is to deliver a functional application that meets the customer''s requirements. After uploading, however, everything does not always work the way it is written in the documentation. However, the responsible developer can avoid potential problems with a brief discussion with the application operator on scaling, redundancy and performance. For example, a weighty task, often overlooked, is a key task. They help uncover the tight throat and predict when the infrastructure will need to be restored. Infrastructure scaling is often "intuitive" when estimated performance is estimated based on the expected number of users based on past experience. When it comes to estimating, it is difficult to reveal a narrow throat that can be in the application - if the application is not tested under a lot of load, it is very likely that the power is under-shot or cracked. But there is also the question of scalability - if I add another server, will it help? Applications often do not run linearly, which means that doubling the number of servers does not have to double the number of customers the client can serve. There may even be a narrow throat when adding more power will not help any more. Do you know how your app scrolls?</p>\r\n<h3>Development, testing and documentation</h3>\r\n<p>Another common problem is that developers do not provide documentation for the application. We call it "It works on my laptop!" Developer has its own development environment where the application tests it during development. It then sends the hosting company or the "finished product" platform, and the deployment expert determines the configuration of the server, which modules of the application framework and its application works. The developer''s response is always about the specific problem of why the application does not work, install ImageMagick, "and it is not clear to the developer whether the application has functional requirements for running. However, this is important in terms of operation, not only for the initial startup but also for possible upgrades of the infrastructure, operating system, application server, etc. To solve this problem, it is good to take two steps: Have a specific test environment that resembles as much as possible the production environment (and it''s not a developer''s notebook or a "server" in the kitchen below the table). This test environment is good to maintain and test any changes on the production platform. In the test environment, we can also test new versions of packages and security patches. The second step is to get developers to upload the application with up-to-date installation and operating documentation.</p>\r\n<p>DIGMIA has been working on systems for a long time - this year we celebrated our 10th birthday! We run large Slovak and foreign portals, critical business systems across industries, or network infrastructure for demanding customers, such as terrestrial broadcasting. With our sophisticated monitoring and non-stop hotline, our customer''s applications work faster and more cost-effectively. Our unique experienced experts have access to the latest technologies and knowledge. In addition, we love open-source software, we also contribute to its development and we prefer it to client solutions. And we also enjoy working with developers. Our extensive experience in deploying operations and scalable redundant server farms can save them a lot of work and worries. And ultimately, the most important satisfied customer is the one who works.</p>', '', NULL, NULL, '[]', '', '2018-12-04 15:03:38', 558, '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2018-12-05 19:44:05', 558, '2018-12-04 15:03:38', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 1, 3, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 2, '{"catItemTitle":"","catItemTitleLinked":"","catItemFeaturedNotice":"","catItemAuthor":"0","catItemDateCreated":"","catItemRating":"","catItemImage":"","catItemIntroText":"","catItemExtraFields":"","catItemHits":"","catItemCategory":"","catItemTags":"","catItemAttachments":"","catItemAttachmentsCounter":"","catItemVideo":"","catItemVideoWidth":"","catItemVideoHeight":"","catItemAudioWidth":"","catItemAudioHeight":"","catItemVideoAutoPlay":"","catItemImageGallery":"","catItemImageGalleryWidth":"","catItemImageGalleryHeight":"","catItemDateModified":"","catItemReadMore":"","catItemCommentsAnchor":"0","catItemK2Plugins":"","itemDateCreated":"","itemTitle":"","itemFeaturedNotice":"","itemAuthor":"0","itemFontResizer":"","itemPrintButton":"0","itemEmailButton":"0","itemSocialButton":"0","itemVideoAnchor":"","itemImageGalleryAnchor":"","itemCommentsAnchor":"0","itemRating":"0","itemImage":"","itemImgSize":"","itemImageMainCaption":"","itemImageMainCredits":"","itemIntroText":"","itemFullText":"","itemExtraFields":"","itemDateModified":"","itemHits":"","itemCategory":"","itemTags":"","itemAttachments":"","itemAttachmentsCounter":"","itemVideo":"","itemVideoWidth":"","itemVideoHeight":"","itemAudioWidth":"","itemAudioHeight":"","itemVideoAutoPlay":"","itemVideoCaption":"","itemVideoCredits":"","itemImageGallery":"","itemImageGalleryWidth":"","itemImageGalleryHeight":"","itemNavigation":"","itemComments":"0","itemTwitterButton":"0","itemFacebookButton":"0","itemGooglePlusOneButton":"0","itemAuthorBlock":"0","itemAuthorImage":"0","itemAuthorDescription":"0","itemAuthorURL":"0","itemAuthorEmail":"0","itemAuthorLatest":"0","itemAuthorLatestLimit":"","itemRelated":"","itemRelatedLimit":"","itemRelatedTitle":"","itemRelatedCategory":"","itemRelatedImageSize":"","itemRelatedIntrotext":"","itemRelatedFulltext":"","itemRelatedAuthor":"","itemRelatedMedia":"","itemRelatedImageGallery":"","itemK2Plugins":""}', '', 'robots=\nauthor=', '', '', 'en-GB'),
(64, 'Do you know how the face recognition technology works?', 'doyou-know-how-the-face-recognition-technology-works', 1, 1, '<h3>What is face recognition?</h3>\r\n<p>The motive for writing this article was pretty simple. Amazon Rekognition, when I wandered around Amazon and tried to find a thing I did not necessarily need. After a moment of searching and wandering about what actually happens, I came across a very simple definition of how Rekognition actually works. This is Amazon Web Services (AWS) technology and workshop, which provides high-precision face analysis and face recognition on images and videos you provide. Amazon Rekognition is based on the highly scalable, learning-savvy technology developed by Amazon scientists. Based on analyzes of billions of images and videos daily, it does not require experience and expertise with machine learning systems. But the story does not end there. Forbes Magazine has decided to test this solution. He has found very interesting things, and so, besides a very cheap solution, this is an extremely accurate solution.</p>\r\n<p>Based on photos voluntarily provided by staff in Jersey and London, the people around Thomas Fox-Brewster were able to put an extremely accurate Face Detection solution after a few hours. The first step was to set up the AWS database - "S3 bucket" with whom he has recorded various random photographs along with his employees'' (Las Vegas criminals) photos. Rekognition does not have a simple face-to-face visualization and matching tool that results in text output. Therefore, with the help of an independent programmer, a simple script was written, marking a green square around the faces of the people who were not in the database or the red square of those who were in the database. In order for Rekognition to compare faces with databases, a "fake" record was recorded that simulated images from CCTV cameras. Based on the information provided by Thomas in his article, the results were surprising not only with their accuracy but also with the speed of response. What''s even more remarkable is the price of a solution from AWS to solve this size, which according to published information would not exceed $ 10.</p>\r\n<p>"Face recognition" technology is the technology capable of recognizing and identifying people from digital photos and face recognition videos. The way these systems work are a few but generally most of them work by comparing selected facial features from a given image with facial features within a database. Normally, this technology is used in security and security systems, but with the growing number of smart technologies, it is clear that the use of face recognition will be applicable in other areas as well. But the question remains security and protection of scrubs.</p>', '', NULL, NULL, '[]', '', '2018-12-04 15:10:13', 558, '', 558, '2018-12-05 19:43:09', '2018-12-04 16:41:15', 558, '2018-12-04 15:10:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 1, 4, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 3, '{"catItemTitle":"","catItemTitleLinked":"","catItemFeaturedNotice":"","catItemAuthor":"0","catItemDateCreated":"","catItemRating":"","catItemImage":"","catItemIntroText":"","catItemExtraFields":"","catItemHits":"","catItemCategory":"","catItemTags":"","catItemAttachments":"","catItemAttachmentsCounter":"","catItemVideo":"","catItemVideoWidth":"","catItemVideoHeight":"","catItemAudioWidth":"","catItemAudioHeight":"","catItemVideoAutoPlay":"","catItemImageGallery":"","catItemImageGalleryWidth":"","catItemImageGalleryHeight":"","catItemDateModified":"","catItemReadMore":"","catItemCommentsAnchor":"0","catItemK2Plugins":"","itemDateCreated":"","itemTitle":"","itemFeaturedNotice":"","itemAuthor":"0","itemFontResizer":"","itemPrintButton":"0","itemEmailButton":"0","itemSocialButton":"0","itemVideoAnchor":"","itemImageGalleryAnchor":"","itemCommentsAnchor":"0","itemRating":"0","itemImage":"","itemImgSize":"","itemImageMainCaption":"","itemImageMainCredits":"","itemIntroText":"","itemFullText":"","itemE