(550, 53, 1, '', '2018-12-05 19:32:16', 558, 8885, '454d88f8f5a22ed6539146206063081b6c5ba9e5', '{"id":53,"asset_id":314,"title":"How to prepare for GDPR?","alias":"how-to-prepare-for-gdpr","introtext":"<p>&lt;p&gt;Peter Fuska, CEO of Digmia, about what will bring the new GDPR regulation to individuals and businesses, what does that mean in practice and how companies can prepare for it. Please read the interview or watch the video.&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;h3&gt;What changes does the new OU do for businesses? h3&amp;gt;&lt;\\/h3&gt;<br \\/>&lt;p&gt;The new EU Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) enters into force uniformly throughout the EU on 25 May 2018. The Regulation provides for increased protection of individuals in the processing of personal data, in particular by entrepreneurs and public administrations and self-governments. For natural persons, this extends the scope of the rights they may apply to the processing of personal data, such as the right to transfer personal data, the limitation of processing or the complete deletion of personal data. Similarly, entrepreneurs and institutions (whether in the position of an operator or an intermediary) introduce obligations that an entrepreneur has to meet if a natural person wants to exercise his rights in the area of \\u200b\\u200bpersonal data protection.&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;h3&gt;What specific principles or principles of protection the OU brings and what does it mean in practice?&lt;\\/h3&gt;<br \\/>&lt;p&gt;The Regulation defines eight principles that will govern the processing of personal data of the individuals concerned. I will only mention the key: the principle of legality and purpose limitations, we can obtain personal information only for a specific purpose and process it only in a way that is compatible for that purpose. For the purpose of defining the purpose, the entrepreneur has either support in other laws (eg the Social \\/ Health Insurance Act when collecting OU when reporting a worker to a social or health insurance company) or processing necessary for performance of the contract or for pre-contractual arrangements (eg when buying a holiday or tickets) or there is a legitimate interest of the businessman in processing (eg, the protection of his \\/ her own property when entering the premises). Of course, personal data can be processed based on the consent of the natural person, which in many cases will be the only legal solution. The principle of minimization in terms of the extent and duration of the retention of personal data, the entrepreneur has to check, for example, for the purpose of the selection process, only collects the data relevant for decision-making on candidates and will not be able to keep the resumes of unsuccessful candidates for a long time after the selection and occupation of the position (many managers will find such CVs in their emails or folders). The principle of integrity and confidentiality, the entrepreneur must have adequate technical means and measures in place to ensure the security of personal data and to prevent unauthorized access, damage or loss of personal data.&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;p&gt;There is a fairly wide range of technical means, I would certainly start with areas where there is a high level of vulnerability - PC protection, especially laptops, that workers normally transfer between work and home. Introducing disk encryption on your laptop is key to data protection in case of theft. It is also important to protect data in the electronic data transfer between company headquarters and external parties - transmission via an encrypted VPN tunnel as a necessity for personal data to be captured and misused. Managing employee access to personal data is particularly important in minimizing personal data misuse inside the company. It is recommended to introduce a 2-factor authentication that requires additional authentication of the person accessing personal data (eg token) in addition to logins and passwords.&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;h3&gt;. to lose or steal personal data, what steps do you need on the operator side?&lt;\\/h3&gt;<br \\/>&lt;p&gt;At first it is important to judge how high the likelihood that theft, the laptop will lead to a high risk from the point of view of the rights of the individuals concerned. If a doctor stole a notebook with an unencrypted disk that has sensitive patient health data, the risk is high and the operator is required to report an incident to the Office for Personal Data Protection within 72 hours of its occurrence. It is also necessary to inform the affected person of such breach \\/ incidents. In order to communicate with the Authority and the persons concerned, it is appropriate to have a so- responsible person. However, not every operator must necessarily have such a person - it concerns, for example, public authorities or processors who process specific categories of data such as genetic, biometric, health, and so on.&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;h3&gt;The new Regulation enters into force on 25 May 2018. How are entrepreneurs and institutions prepared and what do you need to do to comply with this regulation?&lt;\\/h3&gt;<br \\/>&lt;p&gt;Many, in particular, small and medium-sized businesses have been convinced that the regulation does not concern them, or they intervene very marginally, and that''s why they did not get them. However, when we realize that personal data is most often a part of customer and employee data (every entrepreneur has customers and the vast majority also employs individuals), the regulation can not be avoided. In terms of readiness, most entrepreneurs are in the first - analytical phase in which they identify where processes \\/ functional areas are or are not in line with the Regulation. The part (rather minority) has a ready-made implementation plan and has begun introducing measures for critical areas. To achieve compliance, each processor should have at least three basic steps:&lt;\\/p&gt;<br \\/>&lt;ul&gt;<br \\/>&lt;li&gt;Perform a so-called GAP analysis, i. view your business processes, map your personal data flowing through the organization, and assess where the areas do not meet the requirements of the regulation (eg to assess or have a purpose for collecting and processing personal data)&lt;\\/li&gt;<br \\/>&lt;li&gt;Prepare a draft measure, evaluate it in terms of cost and time, and create an implementation plan&lt;\\/li&gt;<br \\/>&lt;li&gt;Run the implementation of steps that can cover the areas of: o Technical (IT) - encryption, pseudonymization, 2-factor authentication and others o Organizational - change of scope of collected personal data in processes, modifications in the entitlements of personnel processing personal data or change physical access to premises where sensitive personal information is processed. o Legal and documentation - preparation of texts for consent to the processing of personal data, preparation and signing of processing contracts with business partners, eventually introducing a code of conduct, etc.&lt;\\/li&gt;<br \\/>&lt;\\/ul&gt;<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"25","created":"2018-12-05 19:32:16","created_by":"558","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2018-12-05 19:32:16","modified_by":null,"checked_out":null,"checked_out_time":null,"publish_up":"2018-12-05 19:32:16","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"images\\\\\\/articles\\\\\\/542390225756f78888142d54f3d17e01.jpg\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_b